⭐ Laravel Basic Routing (Complete Explanation)

Routing is one of the core concepts of Laravel. It defines how application responds to user requests (URLs).

🔷 1. What is Routing?

Routing is the process of mapping a URL (request) to a specific function or controller method in Laravel.

👉 In simple terms:

URL → decides what code will run

🔷 2. Where Routes are Defined?

Laravel routes are written in:

routes/web.php   → for web applications
routes/api.php   → for APIs

🔷 3. Basic Route Syntax
Route::method('/url', function () {
    return 'Hello World';
});

🔷 4. Types of Basic Routes
🟢 1. GET Route (Most Common)

Used to fetch data or display pages

Route::get('/home', function () {
    return 'Welcome to Home Page';
});


👉 When user visits:

http://localhost:8000/home

🟢 2. POST Route

Used to send data to server

Route::post('/submit', function () {
    return 'Data Submitted';
});

🟢 3. PUT Route

Used to update full data

Route::put('/update', function () {
    return 'Data Updated';
});

🟢 4. DELETE Route

Used to delete data

Route::delete('/delete', function () {
    return 'Data Deleted';
});

🟢 5. ANY Route

Accepts all HTTP methods

Route::any('/test', function () {
    return 'Any Method Works';
});

🔷 5. Route with Controller (Important)

Instead of writing logic in route, we use Controller.

use App\Http\Controllers\UserController;

Route::get('/user', [UserController::class, 'index']);


👉 Meaning:

/user → URL
UserController@index → method called
🔷 6. Route with Parameters
🟢 Required Parameter
Route::get('/user/{id}', function ($id) {
    return "User ID: " . $id;
});


👉 Example:

/user/10

🟢 Optional Parameter
Route::get('/user/{name?}', function ($name = 'Guest') {
    return $name;
});

🔷 7. Named Routes

Used for easy URL referencing.

Route::get('/profile', function () {
    return 'Profile Page';
})->name('profile');


👉 Usage:

route('profile');

🔷 8. Route Groups

Used to apply common settings to multiple routes.

Example:
Route::prefix('admin')->group(function () {
    Route::get('/dashboard', function () {
        return 'Admin Dashboard';
    });

    Route::get('/users', function () {
        return 'Admin Users';
    });
});


👉 URLs:

/admin/dashboard
/admin/users

🔷 9. Middleware in Routes (Basic idea)
Route::get('/dashboard', function () {
    return 'Dashboard';
})->middleware('auth');


👉 Only logged-in users can access

🔷 10. Route Redirection
Route::redirect('/old', '/new');

🔷 11. Route View Shortcut
Route::view('/welcome', 'welcome');


👉 Directly loads Blade view

🔷 12. Real-Life Analogy

Think of routing like:

🚦 “Traffic Police System”

Concept	Meaning
URL	Road
Route	Traffic rule
Controller	Destination handler
Middleware	Security check
🔷 13. Why Routing is Important?

✔ Controls application flow
✔ Connects URL to logic
✔ Improves code structure
✔ Supports MVC architecture

⭐ Final Summary

👉 Laravel Routing defines how URLs map to functions or controllers. It supports methods like GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, parameters, groups, middleware, and named routes.
